From: dmuir@athena.mit.edu (Douglas Muir)
Crossposted-To: comp.os.ms-windows.advocacy
Subject: Re: NT versus Linux
Date: 26 Aug 1993 16:34:04 GMT

[ Mark Davis' statements about Microsofts questionable bundling practices, 
and Dan Newcomb's response to same deleted ]

Basically, the thing which people object to about Microsoft's bundling deals
(and one of the areas of focus in the rescent FTC probe) is that Microsoft
offers a substantial discount to dealers who bundle DOS on a per CPU basis.
That is, microsoft says something like, "o.k., we'll sell you Dos (plus
liscences, manuals, etc.) at $x per copy for y many copies, or, you can pay us
$z dollars for *every CPU/system* you sell, and include DOS (plus liscences,
manuals, etc) on however many of those CPUs/systems you want." (where z << x)
So, if I call up Gateway and say, "I want a 486..., how much?" they quote
me a price.  I say, "That includes DOS(/Windows)?"  They say yes.  I say,
"How much less if I don't want Dos?"  They say, "Sorry, Dos is included in
the puchase price."  If I push, I might get them to knock of the $15 to $20
they paid for DOS (of course, they still have to pay Microsoft that $15 to $20)
Now, when I ask them to install OS/2 (or UnixWare, NeXTStep, etc.) are they
going to charge me the wholesale price they're getting it for (probably
about half what I'd pay for it retail, if not less - i.e., a price comparable
to the price they were going to "charge" me for DOS) or am I going to have 
to pay the full retail price?  Bingo.

Basically, Microsofts pricing scheme locks out other OS's at the system
purchase level.  If I want a system with OS/2, it's going to cost me about
$200 more than the system with DOS/Windows, even though comparing retail 
prices DOS+Windows is nowhere near $200 cheaper than OS/2.

Of course, the FTC hasn't recommended any action against Microsoft (though 
I hear the Justice Dept. has taken an interest in the case).

-Doug






