From: imp@boulder.parcplace.com (Warner Losh)
Subject: Re: Linux and Corporate America
Date: Thu, 26 Aug 1993 15:42:51 GMT

In article <25gdmjINN6v1@uwm.edu> rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller) writes:
>There are no "Copyright Police".  Violation of Copyright is *not* a crime.

Well, yes and no.  Copyright violation does have specific penalties
associated with it.  These penalties may be "civil" in nature, rather
than "criminal" in nature, but I seem to recall that the FBI can and
will get involved in cases of video tape "piracy."  I fail to see how
that is different than software "piracy," but maybe there is specific
statutes in the USA that make this distinction.

Linus Torvalds, or his agents, can always sue, or threaten to sue,
someone who is violating the terms and conditions of his software.  It
would be relatively easy for him to produce a number of expert
witnesses that would testify that the code in question was written by
Linus, or at the very least collected by him.

>After all, Copyright simply gives you the right to
>sue and an even chance of winning at it.  It doesn't actually stop anyone.

Felony laws do not prevent people from being killed.  They just give
people the right to prosecute and fair chance at winning.  They don't
actually stop anyone. :-)

>I sincerely doubt that there would be *any* legal retaliation.

Depending on the stuation, I can see various groups getting involved
to help out.  The FSF and EFF spring to mind, but I'm sure there are
others.

This thread is starting to stray off the beaten path of FAQs and
failure to read the release notes questions that the comp.os.linux.*
tree is famous for....

BTW, I don't see anything wrong with using Linux as a base to build
things on.  After all, it is only the kernel that is GPL'd, if someone
supply all the other software after that.  And you can point to where
the sources are (or even give them away) for the kernel.  If you don't
have the sources to the rest of the <whatever> system, then they won't
do you much good.  I can see this situation coming up more easily than
I can see someone filing the copyrights off and claiming that he or
she wrote it.

Warner
-- 
Warner Losh             imp@boulder.parcplace.COM       ParcPlace Boulder
I've almost finished my brute force solution to subtlety.

