From: mark@taylor.uucp (Mark A. Davis)
Subject: Re: Linux and Corporate America
Date: Thu, 26 Aug 1993 17:08:38 GMT

rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller - Practical Realist) writes:

>mark@taylor.uucp (Mark A. Davis) writes:

>>There is morality and legality.  It is possible that the GPL'er could sue
>>a violator.  This may not happen because of the money and time needed to
>>do this, but it is a possibility.  If nothing else, there is morality.
>>I would be extremely bad looking if Sun, for example decided to violate
>>the GPL on Linux.  Sun's competitors might be the first to offer legal
>>assistance to Linus..... if you get my meaning.

>Give me a break.  I'll lay even odds that *MOST* Sun users have never even
>*HEARD* of the GNU project!!

Give everyone a break and read the posting before responding.  The above
statement was something called a hypothetical example.  No one is
suggesting that Sun or Sun users would do anything with Linux.
But if a small company
did such a thing to gain competitive advantage and it worked (IE they
were stirring up a controversy) you can bet that other businesses in that
market would flock to defend Linux if it were in THEIR OWN best
interest.  It happens all the time in many industries!

>Don't you get it?  NO ONE HAS HEARD OF US!!  WE ARE A *TINY* MINORITY.
>...and more importantly, we have little if any control over cash flow.

Nobody is denying that.  But something *could* happen in the future 
(mostly volume and features) which would make Linux come to the forground
and get the attention of medium and big companies.  Certainly that is
not the case right now when Linux cannot run existing comercial software.

